# Longest Increasing Subsequence

## Difficulty
Medium

## Approach

Let `LIS[i]` represent the length of the longest increasing subsequence starting at index `i`.

Initialize every value to `1` since each element can form a subsequence of length `1` by itself.

Process the array from right to left. For each index `i`, check all indices `j > i`.

If:

```text
nums[i] < nums[j]
```

then `nums[j]` can extend the increasing subsequence starting at `i`, so update:

```text
LIS[i] = max(LIS[i], 1 + LIS[j])
```

The answer is the maximum value in the `LIS` array.

## Complexity

- **Time Complexity:** O(n²)
- **Space Complexity:** O(n)

## Code

```python
class Solution(object):
    def lengthOfLIS(self, nums):
        LIS = [1] * len(nums)

        for i in range(len(nums) - 1, -1, -1):
            for j in range(i + 1, len(nums)):
                if nums[i] < nums[j]:
                    LIS[i] = max(LIS[i], 1 + LIS[j])

        return max(LIS)
```
